review_blob: Looks good, but the taste doesnt match up with the appearance. Pours copper with a thin head that doesnt last long. A medium-strong hops flavor, but not much else. maybe pine, a little nutty, but not in a good way. Better than generic American beer, but not up to my expectations.

Beautiful reddish-amber color, nice body, clean caramel head poured about three fingers high and endured well. Light aroma and a very pleasant taste -- citrus, hops, pine and a slight bitterness in the finish. Overall, a very pleasing and enjoyable beer.

I greatly enjoyed this beer, having tried it twice now. I went out and purchased four extras to share with friends -- hopefully will be able to resist opening one and let it age for a few years to see how this tastes in the future. Thanks to the wine that is blended in, it has a very unique taste -- delicate and fruity and cheerful when cold -- more robust and sophisticated as it warms up. Incredibly drinkable, alcohol seems almost completely masked. There is a spice to it I cant put my finger on, but no matter how you drink it, it is very refreshing and I think would pair well with almost any meal -- from burgers to sushi.

An excellent beer -- well balanced, sweet and clear, with a smell that will seduce you from across the room. Nice head finish. ...And leaps and bounds the best thing available by the keg in Dallas -- at a friends birthday party, this ended up being the only thing available and at some point, we were using this for beer pong -- best tasting game Ive ever played.

A fantastic beer for all occasions. Slightly hazy amber color. Not as hoppy as you would think, especially compared to Victory beers like Hops Wallop, but better balanced overall. Citrus, hops, caramel, and a full, rich flavor for an IPA, and cheaper than most of Victorys other beers, which is a big plus when having friends over. For the money, one of my favorite beers to serve to guests.

This is a pleasant beer for a summer evening -- well rounded, spicy-citrus-honey flavor. Very strong, so be careful. Pleasant honey-color, nice off-white head when poured. Enjoyable, especially for a triple, but its not my favorite style. Gets bonus points for a great name.

Hands down one of my favorite beers and the only thing I consistently try to keep stocked in my fridge. In my limited experience, this is the best beer that is widely available -- by the six pack -- in my area. Pours like old motor oil aned has a slick residue on the sides of the glass and a glorious aroma and flavor of burnt chocolate/coffee/chestnut. Has a wonderful, tan head when poured and is smoooooth for an Imperial Stout.

The deScription is accurate on one thing -- very hoppy taste, but relatively light on the aroma. Very hazy yellow -- you cant see through a glass no matter how you hold it up to the light. Almost no head at all, no matter how you pour it, but a gauze of tiny white bubbles across the top. In going through a six-pack slowly over the last month or so, this beer has gradually grown on me. Originally, I didnt like it nearly as well as Victorys HopsDevil, which is probably sitting right next to it on the shelf at your store, but it is a very respectable beer in its own right, and has a distinct bitter finish that has grown on me, as well as a nice little kick from being a doubleIPA. Id call it something of a developed taste, but very enjoyable.
